# =============================================================================
# What TO COMMIT (examples of files you typically want to include)
# =============================================================================
# These are comments showing what you SHOULD commit:

# ✅ Commit these:
# - .env.example (template)
# - glossary source files (*.csv, *.json, *.yaml)
# - configuration templates
# - documentation (README.md, docs/)
# - scripts (without credentials)
# - CI/CD configuration files
# - requirements.txt, package.json
# - .gitignore itself

# ❌ Never commit these:
# - .env (actual environment variables)
# - credentials, tokens, passwords
# - generated backup files
# - personal IDE settings
# - temporary files
# - large generated files

# =============================================================================
# Security Considerations
# =============================================================================
# Always review files before committing to ensure:
# 1. No credentials or secrets are included
# 2. No personal information is exposed
# 3. No internal API endpoints or configurations
# 4. No large binary files that don't belong in version control

# Use 'git add -p' to review changes line by line
# Use 'git diff --cached' to review staged changes before committing
# Consider using pre-commit hooks to catch sensitive data
